In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding methods:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI `Window` override |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |
| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnStopped()` |
| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `OnActivated()` |

**Example:**

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()
    {
        base.OnCreated();
        // replaces OnStart
    }

    protected override void OnDeactivated()
    {
        base.OnDeactivated();
        // replaces OnSleep
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // replaces OnResume
    }
}
```

Then in your `App` class, override `CreateWindow`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new MyWindow(new MainPage());
}
```

Alternatively, you can hook **platform-specific lifecycle events** via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` if you need finer-grained control (e.g., Android's `OnPause` vs `OnStop`).
